            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ö° Government Powers Created</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Judge Elections & Qualifications</strong> ‚Äî Each chamber determines if members are properly elected and qualified</li>
              <li><strong>Quorum Rules</strong> ‚Äî Majority needed to conduct official business</li>
              <li><strong>Rulemaking Authority</strong> ‚Äî Each chamber creates its own procedural rules</li>
              <li><strong>Disciplinary Power</strong> ‚Äî Can punish members for misconduct</li>
              <li><strong>Expulsion Power</strong> ‚Äî Can expel members with 2/3 vote</li>
              <li><strong>Journal Requirement</strong> ‚Äî Must publish official proceedings</li>
              <li><strong>Recorded Votes</strong> ‚Äî Must record votes when 1/5 of members request</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">üö´ Government Restrictions</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Cannot Exclude Qualified Members</strong> ‚Äî Must seat members who meet constitutional qualifications (Powell v. McCormack)</li>
              <li><strong>Expulsion Requires 2/3 Vote</strong> ‚Äî Cannot remove members with simple majority</li>
              <li><strong>Must Keep Public Journal</strong> ‚Äî Proceedings cannot be entirely secret</li>
              <li><strong>Cannot Adjourn Alone</strong> ‚Äî Neither chamber can adjourn for more than 3 days without other's consent</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT define specific rules each chamber must follow (e.g., filibuster)</li>
              <li>Does NOT require unanimous consent or supermajorities for regular business</li>
              <li>Does NOT mandate televised proceedings</li>
              <li>Does NOT specify penalties for member misconduct short of expulsion</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Powell v. McCormack (1969)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Congress cannot refuse to seat an elected member who meets the three constitutional qualifications. 
                  "Judging qualifications" means verifying constitutional requirements, not adding new ones.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* SECTION 6 */}
        <div id="section-6" className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-2">
            Section 6 ‚Äî Compensation & Privileges
          </h3>
          
          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">ÔøΩ Exact Constitutional Text (Key Excerpts)</h4>
            <div className="space-y-3">
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "The Senators and Representatives shall receive a Compensation for their Services, to be ascertained by Law, 
                and paid out of the Treasury of the United States."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "They shall in all Cases, except Treason, Felony and Breach of the Peace, be privileged from Arrest during 
                their Attendance at the Session of their respective Houses..."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "...for any Speech or Debate in either House, they shall not be questioned in any other Place."
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">ÔøΩüí≠ Plain English Translation</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700">
              Members of Congress are paid by the federal treasury. They cannot be arrested while attending or traveling to/from 
              Congress (except for treason, felony, or breach of peace). They cannot be questioned elsewhere for speeches or 
              debates in Congress. No member can hold another federal office while serving in Congress, and no one can serve 
              in Congress while holding a federal office created or whose pay was increased during their term.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ö° Government Powers Created</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Federal Compensation</strong> ‚Äî Congress paid from U.S. Treasury (not by states)</li>
              <li><strong>Speech or Debate Clause</strong> ‚Äî Members protected from liability for legislative speech</li>
              <li><strong>Limited Arrest Immunity</strong> ‚Äî Cannot be arrested while attending or traveling to/from Congress sessions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">üö´ Government Restrictions</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Incompatibility Clause</strong> ‚Äî Cannot hold other federal office while in Congress</li>
              <li><strong>Ineligibility/Emoluments Clause</strong> ‚Äî Cannot be appointed to federal office created or enriched during their term</li>
              <li><strong>Arrest Immunity Limited</strong> ‚Äî No protection for treason, felony, or breach of peace</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT grant absolute immunity from prosecution</li>
              <li>Does NOT prevent civil lawsuits for actions outside legislative duties</li>
              <li>Does NOT specify congressional salary amount (set by law)</li>
              <li>Does NOT protect members from prosecution for criminal activity</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Gravel v. United States (1972)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Speech or Debate Clause protects legislators and their aides for legislative acts, but does not shield 
                  them from criminal prosecution for non-legislative conduct.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-yellow-50 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 p-4 mt-4">
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">
              <strong>Note:</strong> The 27th Amendment (1992) prevents congressional pay raises from taking effect until 
              after an intervening election.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* SECTION 7 */}
        <div id="section-7" className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-2">
            Section 7 ‚Äî How Bills Become Laws
          </h3>
          
          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">ÔøΩ Exact Constitutional Text (Key Excerpts)</h4>
            <div className="space-y-3">
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "All Bills for raising Revenue shall originate in the House of Representatives; but the Senate may propose 
                or concur with Amendments as on other Bills."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "Every Bill which shall have passed the House of Representatives and the Senate, shall, before it become a 
                Law, be presented to the President of the United States; If he approve he shall sign it, but if not he shall 
                return it, with his Objections..."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "If after such Reconsideration two thirds of that House shall agree to pass the Bill, it shall be sent... 
                to the other House... and if approved by two thirds of that House, it shall become a Law."
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">ÔøΩüí≠ Plain English Translation</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700">
              All bills for raising revenue must start in the House, but the Senate can propose amendments. Every bill that 
              passes both chambers goes to the President. The President can sign it (becomes law), veto it (sent back to 
              Congress), or do nothing for 10 days (becomes law unless Congress adjourns). Congress can override a veto with 
              a 2/3 vote in both chambers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ö° Legislative Process Powers</h4>
            <ol className="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Revenue Bills Originate in House</strong> ‚Äî Tax and spending bills must start in House</li>
              <li><strong>Bicameral Passage Required</strong> ‚Äî Both chambers must pass identical bill text</li>
              <li><strong>Presentment to President</strong> ‚Äî All bills go to President for signature</li>
              <li><strong>Presidential Veto Power</strong> ‚Äî President can reject bills and return with objections</li>
              <li><strong>Congressional Override</strong> ‚Äî 2/3 vote in each chamber overrides veto</li>
              <li><strong>Pocket Veto</strong> ‚Äî Bill dies if Congress adjourns within 10 days and President doesn't sign</li>
              <li><strong>Default Passage</strong> ‚Äî Bill becomes law if President takes no action for 10 days (while Congress in session)</li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">üö´ Government Restrictions</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Cannot Skip Bicameralism</strong> ‚Äî Both chambers must pass identical text</li>
              <li><strong>Cannot Skip Presentment</strong> ‚Äî President must have opportunity to sign or veto</li>
              <li><strong>President Cannot Line-Item Veto</strong> ‚Äî Must veto entire bill (Clinton v. City of New York)</li>
              <li><strong>Cannot Use Legislative Vetoes</strong> ‚Äî INS v. Chadha invalidated one-house vetoes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT allow President to amend bills (only sign or veto)</li>
              <li>Does NOT permit Senate to originate revenue bills</li>
              <li>Does NOT define "revenue" precisely (courts have interpreted broadly)</li>
              <li>Does NOT specify how Congress conducts internal legislative processes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">INS v. Chadha (1983)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Legislative vetoes are unconstitutional. Congress must follow bicameralism (both houses) and presentment 
                  (to President) when taking legislative action. One-house vetoes violate Article I procedures.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Clinton v. City of New York (1998)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Line-item veto is unconstitutional. President cannot cancel parts of bills after signing them into law. 
                  The veto power is all-or-nothing for each bill.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4 mt-4">
            <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">üìä How a Bill Becomes Law</h5>
            <ol className="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Bill introduced in House or Senate (revenue bills must start in House)</li>
              <li>Committee review and markup</li>
              <li>Floor debate and vote in first chamber</li>
              <li>If passed, sent to second chamber for same process</li>
              <li>If both chambers pass identical text, sent to President</li>
              <li>President signs (law), vetoes (returns to Congress), or waits 10 days</li>
              <li>If vetoed, Congress can override with 2/3 vote in each chamber</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* SECTION 8 */}
        <div id="section-8" className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-blue-600 pb-2">
            Section 8 ‚Äî Powers of Congress (Enumerated Powers)
          </h3>
          
          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">ÔøΩ Exact Constitutional Text (Key Clause)</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
              "The Congress shall have Power To lay and collect Taxes, Duties, Imposts and Excises, to pay the Debts and 
              provide for the common Defence and general Welfare of the United States... To make all Laws which shall be 
              necessary and proper for carrying into Execution the foregoing Powers..."
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">üí≠ Plain English Translation</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              This section lists the specific powers granted to Congress. These are called <strong>"enumerated powers"</strong> 
              because they are specifically listed. Congress has no general legislative authority ‚Äî only the powers granted here. 
              The final "Necessary and Proper Clause" allows Congress to make laws needed to carry out these enumerated powers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ö° Congressional Powers Include:</h4>
            <div className="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
              <div className="bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Fiscal Powers</h5>
                <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-700 text-sm ml-2">
                  <li>Tax and collect revenues</li>
                  <li>Borrow money on U.S. credit</li>
                  <li>Coin money and regulate its value</li>
                  <li>Punish counterfeiting</li>
                  <li>Establish uniform bankruptcy laws</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Commerce Powers</h5>
                <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-700 text-sm ml-2">
                  <li>Regulate interstate commerce</li>
                  <li>Regulate foreign commerce</li>
                  <li>Regulate commerce with Indian tribes</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Defense & Foreign Affairs</h5>
                <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-700 text-sm ml-2">
                  <li>Declare war</li>
                  <li>Raise and support armies</li>
                  <li>Provide and maintain a navy</li>
                  <li>Make rules for armed forces</li>
                  <li>Call forth militia</li>
                  <li>Define/punish piracy and international law violations</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Other Powers</h5>
                <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-700 text-sm ml-2">
                  <li>Establish post offices and post roads</li>
                  <li>Protect patents and copyrights</li>
                  <li>Create federal courts below Supreme Court</li>
                  <li>Govern District of Columbia</li>
                  <li>Govern federal property</li>
                  <li>Establish naturalization rules</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">üö´ Government Restrictions</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Limited to Enumerated Powers</strong> ‚Äî Congress cannot claim authority beyond listed powers</li>
              <li><strong>"Necessary and Proper" Is Not Unlimited</strong> ‚Äî Must be tied to an enumerated power</li>
              <li><strong>Commerce Power Has Limits</strong> ‚Äî Cannot regulate purely local activity (Lopez, Morrison)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT grant general "police power" (that belongs to states)</li>
              <li>Does NOT allow Congress to regulate anything it deems important</li>
              <li>Does NOT create federal power over education, marriage, or local criminal law</li>
              <li>Does NOT give unlimited power under "general welfare" (spending clause, not regulatory power)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">McCulloch v. Maryland (1819)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Upheld implied powers under the Necessary and Proper Clause. Congress can charter a national bank as a 
                  means of executing its fiscal powers. "Let the end be legitimate, let it be within the scope of the 
                  Constitution, and all means which are appropriate... are constitutional."
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">United States v. Lopez (1995)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Struck down Gun-Free School Zones Act. The Commerce Clause does not grant Congress power to regulate 
                  non-economic, purely local activity. Possession of a gun near a school is not "interstate commerce."
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Gibbons v. Ogden (1824)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  "Commerce" includes navigation and broadly covers commercial intercourse among states. Federal commerce 
                  power is supreme and excludes state regulation of interstate commerce.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">NFIB v. Sebelius (2012)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Commerce Clause does not permit Congress to mandate purchase of health insurance, but the individual 
                  mandate is permissible as a tax under the Taxing Power.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-600 p-4 mt-4">
            <h5 className="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Necessary and Proper Clause</h5>
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">
              The final clause grants Congress power to "make all Laws which shall be necessary and proper for carrying 
              into Execution the foregoing Powers." This is not a grant of unlimited power, but allows Congress to use 
              reasonable means to execute its enumerated powers.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* SECTION 9 */}
        <div id="section-9" className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-2">
            Section 9 ‚Äî Limits on Federal Government
          </h3>
          
          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">ÔøΩ Exact Constitutional Text (Key Excerpts)</h4>
            <div className="space-y-3">
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "The Privilege of the Writ of Habeas Corpus shall not be suspended, unless when in Cases of Rebellion or 
                Invasion the public Safety may require it."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "No Bill of Attainder or ex post facto Law shall be passed."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "No Money shall be drawn from the Treasury, but in Consequence of Appropriations made by Law; and a regular 
                Statement and Account of the Receipts and Expenditures of all public Money shall be published from time to time."
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">üí≠ Plain English Translation</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700">
              This section lists things the federal government <strong>cannot do</strong>. These are explicit prohibitions 
              on federal power that protect individual liberty and prevent tyranny.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">üö´ Federal Government Prohibited From:</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Suspending Habeas Corpus</strong> ‚Äî Except in rebellion or invasion when public safety requires</li>
              <li><strong>Bills of Attainder</strong> ‚Äî Cannot declare specific person guilty without trial</li>
              <li><strong>Ex Post Facto Laws</strong> ‚Äî Cannot make past actions criminal retroactively</li>
              <li><strong>Direct Taxes Without Apportionment</strong> ‚Äî Must be proportional to census (modified by 16th Amendment)</li>
              <li><strong>Export Taxes</strong> ‚Äî Cannot tax goods exported from any state</li>
              <li><strong>Preference to State Ports</strong> ‚Äî Cannot favor one state's ports over another</li>
              <li><strong>Spending Without Appropriation</strong> ‚Äî No money from Treasury without law</li>
              <li><strong>Secret Spending</strong> ‚Äî Must publish regular financial statements</li>
              <li><strong>Titles of Nobility</strong> ‚Äî Cannot grant noble titles</li>
              <li><strong>Foreign Emoluments</strong> ‚Äî Federal officers cannot accept foreign gifts without consent</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚ö° Rights Protected</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Habeas Corpus</strong> ‚Äî Right to challenge unlawful detention</li>
              <li><strong>No Retroactive Criminal Laws</strong> ‚Äî Protection from ex post facto punishment</li>
              <li><strong>Trial Rights</strong> ‚Äî Cannot be convicted by legislative act (no bills of attainder)</li>
              <li><strong>Financial Transparency</strong> ‚Äî Public has right to know how government spends money</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT prohibit all taxes (only certain types)</li>
              <li>Does NOT prevent temporary suspension of habeas corpus in emergencies</li>
              <li>Does NOT ban all retrospective laws (only criminal ex post facto laws)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Ex parte Milligan (1866)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Civilian courts cannot be replaced by military tribunals when civilian courts are functioning, even during 
                  wartime. Habeas corpus protects against unlawful military detention of civilians.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">United States v. Lovett (1946)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Struck down law that barred specific named individuals from federal employment as a bill of attainder. 
                  Congress cannot legislatively determine guilt and impose punishment.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-600 p-4 mt-4">
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">
              <strong>Purpose:</strong> These limits protect individual liberty and prevent federal tyranny. They establish 
              fundamental rights like habeas corpus and prohibit arbitrary or retroactive punishment.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* SECTION 10 */}
        <div id="section-10" className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-red-600 pb-2">
            Section 10 ‚Äî Limits on State Governments
          </h3>
          
          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">ÔøΩ Exact Constitutional Text (Key Excerpts)</h4>
            <div className="space-y-3">
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "No State shall enter into any Treaty, Alliance, or Confederation; grant Letters of Marque and Reprisal; 
                coin Money; emit Bills of Credit; make any Thing but gold and silver Coin a Tender in Payment of Debts; 
                pass any Bill of Attainder, ex post facto Law, or Law impairing the Obligation of Contracts..."
              </p>
              <p className="text-gray-700 italic bg-gray-50 p-4 rounded">
                "No State shall, without the Consent of the Congress, lay any Imposts or Duties on Imports or Exports... 
                keep Troops, or Ships of War in time of Peace, enter into any Agreement or Compact with another State, 
                or with a foreign Power, or engage in War, unless actually invaded..."
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">üí≠ Plain English Translation</h4>
            <p className="text-gray-700">
              This section lists things that <strong>states cannot do</strong>. It prevents states from acting like 
              independent nations and ensures national unity under the Constitution.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">üö´ States Absolutely Prohibited From:</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Foreign Relations</strong> ‚Äî Cannot make treaties or alliances</li>
              <li><strong>Letters of Marque</strong> ‚Äî Cannot authorize private warfare at sea</li>
              <li><strong>Coining Money</strong> ‚Äî Cannot create their own currency</li>
              <li><strong>Paper Money</strong> ‚Äî Cannot emit bills of credit</li>
              <li><strong>Legal Tender</strong> ‚Äî Can only make gold/silver legal tender for debts</li>
              <li><strong>Bills of Attainder</strong> ‚Äî Cannot pass laws declaring guilt without trial</li>
              <li><strong>Ex Post Facto Laws</strong> ‚Äî Cannot make past actions criminal retroactively</li>
              <li><strong>Contracts Clause</strong> ‚Äî Cannot impair the obligation of contracts</li>
              <li><strong>Titles of Nobility</strong> ‚Äî Cannot grant noble titles</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">üö´ States Prohibited Without Congressional Consent:</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Import/Export Duties</strong> ‚Äî Cannot tax imports or exports (except inspection fees)</li>
              <li><strong>Peacetime Military</strong> ‚Äî Cannot keep troops or warships in peacetime</li>
              <li><strong>Interstate Compacts</strong> ‚Äî Cannot enter agreements with other states</li>
              <li><strong>Foreign Agreements</strong> ‚Äî Cannot make compacts with foreign powers</li>
              <li><strong>Warfare</strong> ‚Äî Cannot engage in war unless actually invaded or in imminent danger</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚ö° Protections Created</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li><strong>Single National Currency</strong> ‚Äî Prevents competing state currencies</li>
              <li><strong>One Foreign Policy</strong> ‚Äî Only federal government conducts foreign relations</li>
              <li><strong>Contract Rights</strong> ‚Äî States cannot void or impair existing contracts</li>
              <li><strong>No Retroactive Criminal Laws</strong> ‚Äî Same protection as federal government</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚ùå What It Does NOT Say</h4>
            <ul className="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-4">
              <li>Does NOT prevent states from regulating local commerce</li>
              <li>Does NOT ban all state cooperation (some compacts allowed with Congress approval)</li>
              <li>Does NOT prevent states from having state defense forces (National Guard)</li>
              <li>Does NOT ban all retrospective laws (only criminal ex post facto)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div className="mb-6">
            <h4 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-600 mb-2">‚öñÔ∏è Key Supreme Court Cases</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">Home Building & Loan Association v. Blaisdell (1934)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Contracts Clause does not absolutely prohibit states from modifying contracts during emergencies. States 
                  can pass debtor-relief laws if reasonable and limited, even if they affect existing contracts.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div className="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded">
                <h5 className="font-bold text-gray-900">U.S. Steel Corp. v. Multistate Tax Commission (1978)</h5>
                <p className="text-gray-700 mt-2">
                  Not all interstate compacts require congressional approval‚Äîonly those that enhance state power at the 
                  expense of federal supremacy or that encroach on federal authority.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-600 p-4 mt-4">
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">
              <strong>Purpose:</strong> Section 10 prevents states from fragmenting national unity. It ensures one currency, 
              one foreign policy, protection of contract rights, and prevents states from becoming competing nations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* Summary */}
        <div className="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-blue-800 text-white rounded-lg p-8 mt-8">
          <h3 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Article I Summary</h3>
          <p className="text-lg leading-relaxed">
            Article I establishes Congress as the first branch of government with <strong>enumerated powers</strong> and 
            important constitutional limits, creating the foundation for all federal legislative authority while preserving 
            the federal system and protecting individual rights.
          </p>
          <p className="mt-4 leading-relaxed">
            It creates a system of <strong>checks and balances</strong> through bicameralism, presidential veto power, 
            and explicit limits on both federal and state authority, ensuring that power remains divided and accountable 
            to the people.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
